The vaccine will be free and voluntary
The vaccine neumococal from January will put an end to the usual customs.
As the first vaccine should be free for families and at the same time.
However, that the compulsory vaccine would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of the free vaccine against neumococos.
The Institute of Medicine is already setting the maximum prices of vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
The experts also already have clear in the procedure of vaccination.
The new vaccine
Free vaccines for children born in August
From January will receive a free vaccine neumococal children born since 2 August last year.
The condition is not having received a dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started with the vaccine last year or earlier, they have to cover other doses of the vaccine.
The first dose of the vaccine must be received between the third and the fifth month of age of the child.
Last year the fourth part of the families left voluntarily to vaccinate their children against pneumococcus.
Parents however paid by a dose 1600 crowns and more.
Smaller To vaccinate children four doses are needed.
Experts estimate that insurance companies will spend in vaccines from 300 to 450 000 SEK annually.
However save in the treatment, which is needed for children not vaccinated.
Until now, the state spent across the vaccination of children around 500 000 annually.
The vaccination cover was initiated by the so - called package of Janota.
The neumococo is the cause of otitis media, but also of the serious infections including meningitis and septicaemia.
Of Neumococales infections in our country each year according to the research in the hospitals 28 children over the age of 10.
In addition to the Czech Republic cover neumócocal vaccine in children was introduced in approximately 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
However at the same time appear views, that this vaccine could be compulsory in future.
From January should be covered by insurance companies and voluntary.
The vaccine would be better, noted for example Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the civic association Nahlas.
Their partnership spreads vaccines neumococales already long ago.
The experts in an international conference, in which our partnership participated, were not completely satisfechoscon the fact that we have the vaccine voluntary.
It is not completely ideal.
On the other hand we are happy, to achieve at least this.
I believe that this is the path that we now have to undertake, mentioned Kalovský.
The Ministry of Health but does not want to change the procedure of vaccination against.
At the moment I do not think at all, said his spokesman.
The voluntary vaccine has its disadvantages, say doctors
The president of the society of pediatricians Odborná společnost praktických dětských lékařů Hana Cabrnochová recognizes, that the voluntary vaccine has its drawbacks.
If all children receive the vaccine, they will think about the reduction of the number of doses. " in the situation, when the vaccine costs a high amount, relatively understand the political decision to have initiated vaccination as a volunteer, " says Cabrnochová.
The experts expect that from next year, more than 80 percent of young parents leaves vaccinate against their babies.
The vaccine neumococal is a big change also because as the first vaccination in children is covered by health companies, not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend more money on prophylaxis, to save in the treatment, explains Cabrnochová.
Doctors will have to buy the vaccine for themselves.
However the pediatricians are worried about the purchase of vaccines.
Previously, the vaccines had to be bought by insurance companies and distributed to doctors, just as when the state gives them other vaccines.
Some members however were afraid, that insurance companies could " get the money of health insurance. "
The Doctors will have to buy vaccines and wait until they are paid by insurance companies.
It is estimated that invest in vaccines 40 thousand a month, which is a significant sum.
It will not be easy, says Cabrnochová.
Still them and us
Can the Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when the Swiss voters have been asked to ban the construction of minarets and that there is a general warning about the alleged Islamisation of Europe, John Bowen, an American academic, wrote a detailed report and studied on the possible integration of Muslims (which in fact are integrating) in one of the most openly societies of the continent.
Some readers will come to this new book as admirers of the last work of the author " what the French do not like the veils " (" why the French don't like Headcarves ") (2006) , a study elegant and argued a problem which divided and worried the country for a decade and a half, and whose effects are still felt today.
The latest book by Mr Bowen has a broader perspective and more ambitious.
As anthropologist, wants to know not only what the politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is actually happening.
Has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now provide the 5-6 million Muslims in France what Mr Bowen called " Islamic spaces.
He is a good listener that reproduces discussions between teachers and students on the questions that concern them more.
Should a Muslim marriage in a mosque or in a city (or both) ?
Should teach young Muslims on the evolution and the rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman to marry a non - Muslim man?
Is it legitimate that a Muslim uses a banking system based on interests to get a mortgage?
Are These seemingly mundane issues, argues, things of daily life, which concern the means more than the political drama.
The author identifies a new generation of priests, teachers and intellectuals, none of them, with the possible exception of Tariq Ramadan, an academic and scholarly Arab Muslim born in Switzerland.
This new generation is to open the debate on how to be at the same time a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
Fail to disseminate this argument.
The Conservatives doubt just the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists that Mr Bowen interview tend to disagree with their counterparts from, supporters of the purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia, who currently have a small but influential presence among Muslims in Europe.
Bowen thinks that the Muslim values and the French secularism could be compatible.
But adaptation requires mutual concessions.
Question to what extent the policymakers French (and the intellectual elite that so fiercely defends the secularism) are truly committed to pluralism.
Suggests that Muslims have probably more unfair treatment that Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who have also had to make their historical commitments with the secular republicanism.
More than a growing pragmatism, perceived " an adjustment of values ".
Can the Islam be French? After reading this book, one tends to say " Yes, but not yet. "
The most devastating of the world
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatic than any other habitat on the planet.
Defining the ice is melting at an alarming rate, taking the life that cannot survive in any other way.
The interests of the oil, gas, transport and fisheries have focused on waters recently open, with diplomats, lawyers and now, as a result of this.
In " on thin ice " (" on thin ice ") Richard Ellis, a writer and illustrator, depicts a natural history of the icon of the North, the polar bear.
Aware of the complicated history and politics of whaling, describes the long tradition of the Arctic explorers, who gave evidence of value to the white bear.
The meeting of the Admiral Nelson as a courageous cadets in 14 years, fighting only with the end of his, is certainly a myth, but others are real.
The offspring, captured while following the bodies of their mothers newly exterminated, were caught and sent to zoos and circuses.
A presentation of circus at the beginning of the 20th century, 75 polar bears at the same time.
Even today, the places of zoos are still generally a part of the area of the scope of an adult savage. The climate is almost never appropriate: a polar bear resident in Singapore was green with algae that grow within the areas without mincing his stripe.
Please click here to learn more!
Ellis uses stories of other writers and historians, and often returned to the threat that hunters presented to the survival of the species.
Although it is banned in Norway, the US and Russia, the killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and Indians Inuits in motonieves use high - powered assault rifles to shoot down their prey.
Ironically, it is in the waters north of those two nations where the ice will last for longer.
In his new book, " after the ice " (" the ice ") , Alun Anderson, a former editor of new Scientist, offers a clear and chilling tale about the science of the Arctic and a daunting look how can transform the future of that place.
It is not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither the atmospheric scientists and oceanographers can adequately explained the speed of change.
It is not for lack of effort.
The travel pioneers of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th century and early 20th century gave evidence for the first time about the movement of the masses of ice.
Then the submarines in the Cold War drew a map of the movedizos belts of ice below the masses of ice.
The satellite and the extensive series of probes fitted into the icebergs are a useful supplement, but individuals resistant camped in the cold still perform many tasks.
Mr Anderson look inside the extraordinary, tiny world of the system tributary within the Arctic ice, formed by chorritos of saline water that while freezing.
But since the bear in the area until the wonders of the Interior, are all condemned once the summer ice withdrawal, which it believes can happen sometime between 2013 and 2050.
In a few months ... these could be us
Marines among the six that placed wreaths on the graves of Arlington
Pfc. Robinson, aged 19, traveled seven hours by bus to place a wreath at the grave of a soldier who had never known.
For him and the other Marines who travelled from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, N. C., to Arlington National Cemetery to decorate graves, it was a day to pay tribute to men and women who were standing in their boots.
In a few months, from where we are embarking, these could be us, said Robinson about the fallen soldiers.
If we, I would like someone to do the same for me, so just try to show respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who met Saturday morning for placing wreaths on the graves of veterans in several sections of the cemetery.
In 1992, Morrill Worcester, the owner of the company Worcester in Harrington, Maine, launched the event when he and others decided to decorate several hundreds of graves in the cemetery in Arlington.
In what is already a tradition of 18 years, and his wife Karen make the journey every year in different cities along the way, to perform events dedicated to military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcester also founded a non - profit organization, wreaths across America, which has spread to other states.
This year the volunteers placed more than 16,000 kroner in the graves of the cemetery, areas in the Pentagon, graves in the cemetery national Fayetteville in Arkansas, the Battery Park in New York City and the memorial site for United Airlines Flight 93 in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second year, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 to buy and transport the crowns.
Charleen Hunt, 70 years, of Westminster, said he made the trip to Arlington in honour of her husband, a career soldier died.
While her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said that this was his way of giving a reward to those who made sacrifices.
This is a modest way in which civilians can support our troops, said.
It is like visiting a grave of family.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, volunteers walked through the fields and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers went to older graves of the First World War, the second World War and the Vietnam war, because they are not as many visits as the new graves, the organisers said.
The atmosphere was joyful while children were playing and the couples were taken in hand, while carrying the fresh pine to the stones sepulcrales.
Every move was a deep green, with a small red ribbon tied at the top.
Near there, the Section 60, where most of the veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, was virtually silent.
The United Service Organizations (Association for the soldier) donated 1,000 kroner to decorate the section, but the grim atmosphere of the current wars invaded the area.
People wept openly, others prayed, and families and friends supported each other in the air.
Some read aloud names carved in stone, while others were inclined to see small white and black plates placed within the mud, for those whose tombstones have not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers who are enjugaban tears in their eyes in front of the grave of her son.
Handled eight hours from Zanesfield, Ohio, to visit the grave of the marine Sgto. David Shane Spicer, who died in combat in July.
No one should never forget why we are free. My son paid for it, he said.
" long after my death I want anyone can remember. "
Cuban officials arrested a contractor of the US government
The Cuban government has arrested a contractor of the US government to mobile and portable computers in the country, said on Saturday the officials of the State Department.
The contractor, which has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc, with headquarters in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for clients such as the Agency for International Development in the United States and the World Bank.
The Consular officers together with the United States Interests Section in Havana are seeking access to the detainee, who was arrested on 5 December.
The specific charges have not been made public, although under Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be detained for almost anything deemed " dangerous ".
All the so - called counter - revolutionary activities, which include minor protests and critics, the risk of arrest.
The graffiti anti government and speeches are considered serious crimes.
Cuba has a nascent community, led by the popular commentator Yoani Sánchez, who often writes about as she and her husband are followed and harassed by government agents.
Sánchez has on several occasions requested permission to leave the country to accept awards, but the permission has been denied.
The arrest of an American contractor can cause tensions between the Communist government of the Castro brothers in Cuba and the Obama administration, which has been looking for a rapprochement " slow pace " to improve relations with the island.
The New York Times was the first to report the news of the arrest on Friday night.
The new American policy emphasizes that if the Cuban government takes concrete steps, such as the release of political prisoners and the creation of more space for the opposition, there will be reciprocity of part of the United States.
The mobile and laptop computers are legal in Cuba, even if they are new products and in a country where the average salary of a worker of the government is $15 per month.
The Cuban government granted ordinary citizens the right to buy mobile only this year; they are used primarily for text messages, since a telephone conversation of 15 minutes would cost the daily wage.
The use of the Internet is extremely limited in the island.
It is available in expensive hotels and hotel for foreign visitors, and establishment of the government, such as universities.
Cubans who want to connect, often have to give their names to the government.
The Access to many websites is restricted.
The arrest of an American in Cuba is unusual.
Glory, press officer in the US Interests Section in Havana, said that most of the handful of American citizens in the prison in Cuba is behind bars for crimes such as drug trafficking.
Berbena said that he could not provide more information on the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly misguided.
An activity that in any other open society would be legal, such as mobile free, in Cuba is a crime, said José Miguel Vivanco, director of the Americas program for Human Rights Watch, which recently published a scathing report on the freedoms in Cuba, Castro, Cuba ", a reference to the site of Raúl Castro as leader of the country, to replace his ailing older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said that the defendants are often arrested, tried and imprisoned in a day.
Said that any solution would probably be political, and that the Cuban government often leads to a negative reaction in the United States, just as the two countries are beginning to have more dialogue.
Pakistani officials Desenmarañan a plot to send men to Afghanistan
On Saturday, the Pakistani authorities to the alleged mastermind of a plot to send five men of Northern Virginia to Afghanistan to kill American troops, saying that they expect the case could help unravel an extensive network of terrorist recruiters, who travel the Internet in search of young radicalized.
The researchers said they were pursuing a mysterious figure insurgent, known as Saifullah, who invited men to Pakistan after discovering that one of them made comments approving terrorist attacks in the Internet video site YouTube.
Saifullah addressed the men once were in Pakistan, trying to help them to reach the remote area in the tribal belt of Pakistan, which is a familiar place for Al Qaeda and its terrorist training camps.
But a Pakistani intelligence official who had been briefed on the case, said on Saturday that Saifullah was unable to convince the commanders of Al Qaeda that men were not part of a plot by the CIA to infiltrate the terrorist network.
Therefore, the isolated for several days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the towering mountains of the northwest which have become a terrorist haven.
They are considered as part of a covert operation.
For this reason were rejected, said the official, who spoke anonymously because of the sensitivity of the case.
The official said that the men were not inmutaron and even were trying to get the proper approval for access to the camps of Al Qaeda, when Pakistani police authorities arrested.
The case of the five men, who remain in Pakistan and are being questioned by the FBI, emphasizes the critical role of the recruiters in the identification of potential terrorists and, perhaps most importantly, determine who are of confidence.
Since the attacks of 11 September 2001, the US intelligence has as top priority try to infiltrate people within al Qaeda.
The recruiters of the organization acting as guards, not leaving those who do not show a serious commitment to the holy war, and those who might be spies.
Analysts said that Al Qaeda analyses with special attention to the applicant American recruits.
But for the organization they represent a huge attraction, due to its potential to have access to American objectives and due to its propaganda value.
But Evan Kohlmann, senior analyst for the Foundation based in the United States, said that the terrorist groups also have become much more cautious in recent years with regard to those who admit, because the American intelligence agencies have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you are trying to infiltrate someone in these groups, what better way to follow the model of recruitment what so many have already followed? said.
It has been transformed into a model based much more on the Web.
