On the other hand, " it can also be said that affect the negotiations, or the freedom of other people.
The data from a test reveal persistent racial differences
The federal ratings last week on the performance in mathematics, was a very good news for public schools in the district capital.
Although the district is still far from the systems with better performance of the country, the report card showed that students in fourth and eighth grade strides at a more rapid pace over the past two years, with regard to the cities of Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what remains engraved in the recent figures from the National Assessment of Educational Progress is the persistent difference in performance between students African - American and white students, both locally and nationally.
The average scores of white students in fourth grade of D. C. during the past two years, grew from 262 to 270 (on a scale of 500) , but their peers African - Americans rose only three points, 209 to 212.
In fact the difference in performance grew between 2007 and 2009, 53 to 58 points.
The progress of African - Americans from the eighth grade remained essentially fixed, dropping a statistically insignificant, 245 to 244.
The average scores of whites were not included in the results of the test, because the sample size was not large enough.
Over an extension of six years, the picture is no more encouraging.
The gap between black and white students in fourth grade in 2003, when it released the first Enpe in the district, was 60 points of the scale (262 to 202) .
Although the scores achieved by children in both groups have increased during this period, the difference has been reduced to 58.
Some lawyers of education in the District expressed concern last week, since progress by the Chancellor Michelle A. Rhee and mayor Adrian M. Fenty (Democrat) , were driven in large part by white students, who are already very good students.
This would suggest that we have improved the whole to those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and controversial, said Jeff Smith, executive director of DC Voice, a non - profit organization that advocates the educational equity in the district.
I am not giving leaps of joy by a difference of two or three points, said the D. C. Council member Kwame R. Brown (Dem. - por accumulation) , who has a daughter in the fourth degree of Eaton elementary.
Brown, a frequent critic of the management style of Rhee, said that the message of the scores of proof is that the secondary schools in the city have a desperate need for attention.
Clearly always want to see the positive signs, and I respect that.
But the concern is that we are not the time nor the energy needed for our middle schools.
Rhee said that the District needs to find better ways to address the needs of the students.
This autumn, for example, is training to some teachers to use a new curriculum of reading, the system of reading Wilson, targeting students in the higher grades of primary and lower secondary school, which dominated the fundamentals of reading in their school and are considerably behind their peers.
The mathematics of every day, a math curriculum from kindergarten to sixth grade, which emphasizes games and real - life experiences, which was introduced in the district under the former superintendent Clifford Janey, which is something of the progress reported by the Enpe last week.
But I think that we need to continue working to offer the best speeches to those students who are below the level of degree, said.
Others say that the results of the Enpe highlight the issue of whether Rhee can further increase the overall performance of the system and still provide additional money and resources for low - performing schools, which will be necessary to reduce the difference.
Here there is a sort of rocky dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a professor of education at the University of California at Berkeley, scores of evidence urban.
The solution of the conventional policy is to devote their resources and reforms to schools located in the poorest sections of the D. C.
Then the objective can generate political implications that go against that timetable.
But the problem, of course, is that, like other cities, she is clinging to the white and black middle class.
Our focus is to ensure that we build a system of excellent schools.
We need to strengthen our schools, so that all families, regardless of where they live, have confidence that their children can access to an excellent public education.
Janey, now superintendent of schools in Newark, said in an interview this week that an essential element to the difference in performance is the year of traditional public school, currently 180 days in the district, to compete with independent schools.
To reach nearly 200 days to have the strength of change, said Janey, which came to an agreement with the Union of their teachers last year in a year of 185 days, which it regards as an " indicator " to seek a greater increase in the next Convention.
To make higher education a more future
The tourist bus came to the University of Gettysburg with a strong.
Graciela Rodríguez, 12 years, fell and blinked during a moment before the white columns, the facades of brick and the meadows.
The parents of Graciela barely had graduated in a secondary school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela itself, who was born in Silver Spring and live in Riverdale, had never set foot in a university campus.
Still, when she and the other pupils of eighth grade of the group explored Gettysburg, where registration costs 38.690 dollars a year, their attitude was less of guests impressed that the potential of enthusiastic students.
Yes! here is where I am! exclaimed Graciela, who would like to study medicine, when the guide announced that they had entered the building of science.
Goodness, seriously? , he said, when the guide spoke of the low proportion of school.
The University of Pennsylvania was the seventh that children had visited during his three - day trip, and had already absorbed completely its deliberate message: the question is not whether you go to university.
The question is what.
Although there is growing concern about the large number of children born in the United States of Hispanic immigrants leave secondary school or become pregnant in adolescence, there are also hundreds of thousands that access to university education they need to access the middle class.
In fact, one in five of these Hispanics " second generation " at the University, a remarkable achievement given that many of their parents, especially Mexicans and Central Americans, entered the United States without finish secondary school.
Their success stories are important, the researchers say, because the way forward for a generation that will play a major role in the labour force of the country.
Those who analysed the higher yield say that often have a natural affinity for school and an innate tendency to succeed.
Many also have parents who set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But the mentoring programmes can also play a role to help Graciela and millions of children like her to go to university, particularly if the efforts are sustained over time.
Noting to low - income children, whose parents do not have the experience and skills to help them navigate the system, it follows that any intervention at any time is not going to solve it, said Patricia Gándara, a researcher at the University of California, Davis, who has studied to students.
We have to think about providing a network of support for these children, from kindergarten to secondary school.
The federal program that funded the tour by the universities of is a useful example.
Known as gear up, provides more than $300 million per year to local school systems, to implement the programmes of preparation, which start when low - income students are in middle school and continue to finish secondary school.
Since 1999, the programme has helped more than 10 million students, with more than 60 per cent the university, according to the United States Department of Education.
The Iraqi oil Ministry reaches agreements with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite the concerns by violence and political instability, the Iraqi government managed to attract major oil companies to rebuild their fragile infrastructure, during two auctions which ended on Saturday.
The 10 agreements that the Iraqi Ministry of oil reached with foreign oil companies suggest that China, Russia and the European oil companies are prepared to play a major role in the restoration of Iraq's oil industry, mutilated by decades of war and sanctions.
American companies are having pujado in only two of the 10 sites.
Seven US companies had paid to participate in the second auction, which began on Friday.
The only presented an offer lost.
Two American companies reached agreements for deposits auctioned in June.
The poor representation of the American oil giants in the opening of the oil industry of Iraq surprised analysts.
Iraq finally opened its doors after six years of war, and instead of American, Asian and European companies to the head, said Ruba Husari, editor of the Forum of oil from Iraq, a centre of online news.
It will be a long time before that something more is on offer in Iraq.
The safety concerns, marked by massive coordinated bombings on Tuesday, and political instability while the American military are withdrawn, probably prevented the American oil companies risk more forcefully in Iraq, which is the third most important reserve of crude oil in the world, said analysts.
US companies were in some cases at a disadvantage, because the rivals, particularly Chinese and other energy companies controlled by the government, have significantly lower labor costs and are more prone to take risks because they are accountable to the shareholders.
Exxon - Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc were the only American companies that reached agreements with the Ministry.
The main American firms, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which have deepened ties with the Iraqi Ministry of oil and have provided technical advice in recent years, empty - handed.
The Russian company Lukoil and Gazprom were the main protagonists in two contracts awarded this weekend.
The National oil Corporation, owned by the Chinese state, in more contracts than any other company and achieved major investments in contracts for two main fields.
We know that China is on track to become a major economic and technological power, said the spokesman of the Ministry of Oil Assam Jihad.
We have confidence that the Chinese company will be on a par with its competitors and will honour its commitments to Iraq.
The companies to submit proposals made offers then with the subsidy per barrel that the ministry was willing to pay to increase production above current levels in each field.
