It is believed that a US missile strike in Pakistan's border with Afghanistan has killed a principal planner of Al Qaeda operations this week, said Friday the US counter - terrorism officials.
If confirmed, this would be the second deadly attack against a senior terrorist leader this autumn.
Saleh was one of the two Arab men are thought to have died on Tuesday when a couple of missiles hit his car, near the town of Miran Shah, in the province of North Waziristan, according to American and Pakistani officials sources in the region.
Local authorities said that the missiles were fired by an unidentified aircraft, of the kind operated by the CIA in the tribal area of Pakistan.
They were driving a white car in the direction of the Afghan border, when the car was hit, said an official of the civilian intelligence agency of Pakistan, speaking by telephone from watching Shah.
The official said that local militants suspected were rushed to the scene and quickly seized what was left of the " bodies completely wrecked. "
Local authorities were unable to verify the identities of the victims, but two American counter - terrorism officials cited unspecified evidence that Somali was among the dead.
Somali was described as a military planner of Al Qaeda, who led the operations outside the region.
Was devoted to conspire around the world, said a senior official, who spoke anonymously, citing the sensitive nature of the American air strikes inside Pakistani territory.
Considering its central role, this probably included attacks against the United States and Europe.
Had a strategic guide of the senior command of Al Qaeda and translated into operational standards for potential terrorist attacks.
The second US official said that Somali had risen rapidly in the ranks of Al Qaeda and was well connected with other extremist groups in the region.
May not be a household name for some Americans, but that in no way diminishes the threat that came to us and our allies, said the second official.
If his death is confirmed, Somali would be the second leader of Al Qaeda or Taliban leader killed since September, when a similar attack killed Najmuddin Jalolov, the leader of a militant faction in the tribal area, and three other high - ranking officers.
The pace of attacks by pilotless aircraft guided by the CIA has declined since the summer, from an average of approximately six operations a month to two, according to an account of the Long War Journal, a Web site run by a non - profit organization.
