Gates: Iran will face additional sanctions
The Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates, said on Friday that world powers will soon " significant additional sanctions against Iran for its failure to engage in talks on its nuclear ambitions.
Gates, speaking to a group of about 300 American troops in northern Iraq, during a trip to a week in war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, he dismissed the prospect of military action against the Islamic Republic.
There are no good options in Iran, he argued, in response to the question of a soldier on the likelihood of such an event.
One of the things that worries me is that, if we have learned anything from Iraq over the past six years, is the inherent unpredictability of the war.
The Obama administration is considering a package of targeted sanctions on Iran's military and political elite, but Gates indicated that some sanctions could also affect the Iranian population in general.
He argued that it would be necessary to " a package of incentives and disincentives ", " to persuade the Iranian government that they would really be less safe with nuclear weapons ", because " its people will suffer greatly " sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement the White House spokesman, Robert Gibbs, the administration joined the European leaders to warn that Iran will face consequences " credible " if its nuclear programme is not fully respects the recommendations of the UN Security Council and its nuclear monitoring body, the International Atomic Energy Agency.
Iran insists it wants to develop nuclear knowledge only for peaceful purposes.
In talks in Geneva on 1 October, indicated that it would negotiate on the restriction of its nuclear programme and would make a substantial part of its stockpile of enriched uranium, in exchange for fuel that is desperately needed for a medical research reactor.
The administration has pushed for this agreement, as a way to build trust between the two sides and make time for negotiations.
But since then, Iran appears to have moved away from the tentative agreements, in part, say experts, because the Iranian leadership is divided with regard to the possibility of engaging with the United States.
Frankly, I think that the hardening of Iran with the international community on some proposals that actually accepted at the beginning of October, has joined the international community, including the Russians and the Chinese, in a way that they have not been in terms of significant additional sanctions against the Iranians, said Gates.
President Obama has set a deadline of 31 December for Iran to respond to the proposals, before other options, including continuing with what the Minister of Foreign Affairs, Hillary Rodham Clinton, once called " devastating sanctions. "
In a statement issued in New York, the mission of Iran to the United Nations denounced what he called the " unfounded and baseless accusations of ", on the part of some members of the Security Council on the nuclear activities of Iran, and said that it is willing to continue talks with the United States and five other world powers, " in order to achieve an appropriate solution, in the long term. "
Gates, who was to return to Washington last Friday, was found in the morning with the Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki, before flying to the Kurdish region of Iraq's oil wealth, to meet with troops in Kirkuk and Kurdish officials in Irbil.
Tensions are high between the Kurds and the Arab majority of Iraq, in particular with regard to the borders, the rights of ownership and partnership.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the potential for conflict, in order to avoid any delay in projects in the United States, to reduce the number of American troops 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
Gates also sought to ease the Kurdish anxiety about the pending reduction. American officials cited the words of gates to Massoud Barzani, the president of the regional government of Kurdistan: " their security, prosperity and autonomy within a unified Iraq.
We will not abandon them. "
In a China that ageing, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by posters of propaganda that the sermoneaban on the fact that " the mother earth is too tired to sustain more children " and " a baby means a grave more. "
Learned the lesson so well that, when government officials in Shanghai, alarmed by the low birth rate and ageing population of their city, changed tack suddenly this summer and began to encourage young couples to have more than one child, his reaction was instant and firm: in any way.
We have already given all our time and energy only for a child.
There is nothing for a second, said Wang, 31, a human resources manager with a child of 8 months.
More than 30 years after that one child policy being introduced in China, creating two generations of children notoriously rechonchos, children alone, apodados " little emperors ", a demographic crisis is emerging in the country.
The average birth rate has plummeted to 1.8 children per couple, compared with the six when the policy was effective, according to the division
Demographic of the UN, while it is anticipated that the number of residents aged 60 and above exploit the 16.7 per cent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 per cent by 2050. This is well above the global average of around 20%.
The imbalance is worse in the rich coastal cities with populations, as Shanghai.
Last year, the people of 60 years and over accounted for almost 22 percent of the residents of Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the family planning Commission and Shanghai municipal population, has said that the fertile couples must have babies to " help reduce the proportion of the ageing population and mitigate future labour shortages. "
Shanghai is about to be " as old (not so rich, however) as developed countries such as Japan and Sweden, " he said.
A gradual relief
Written in the constitution of the country in 1978, the one - child policy is perhaps the most controversial mandate introduced to date by the Communist Party.
Couples who violate the policy face huge fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and job discrimination.
Chinese officials have endorsed the policy for their contribution to avoid a critical pressure on its natural resources, while human rights activists have denounced abuses in the imposition of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced women pregnant with a second child to undergo abortions.
Moreover, many couples have abortions according to the sex of the fetus, leading to a high proportion.
In recent years, the demographic officials have gradually softened its position on the one child policy.
In 2004, allowing more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both the husband and the wife are children only, and in 2007, many of its hard - line slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the institute of Population research at the University of Beijing, said that the central government officials have been discussing recently even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is only son.
In July, Shanghai became the first city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost overnight the morning, posters ordering to the families have only one child, were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be best to have a second child and apply for a permit.
The city government sent to family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples in their homes and slipping leaflets under doors.
It has also promised to provide emotional and financial counseling to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say that the response has been overwhelming.
Disappointing response
Although the officials of a rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai argue that noted a moderate increase in applications for couples who want a second child following the launch of the campaign, more urban districts do not indicate any change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
The disappointed Shanghai officials say that, despite the campaign, it is expected that the number of births in the city in 2010 only reach around 165,000, slightly higher than 2009, but less than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the municipality Caolu in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want more children.
They want to give the best to their first child, said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said he would love to have two children and are legally entitled to do so.
But as many Chinese, have only medical and life insurance that provides them with the government.
Without a network of social protection, they argue, this option would be irresponsible.
People in the West incorrectly the policy of only son as a matter of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
Yes, we are stealing the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not only a political issue.
Is the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the manager of human resources, said that he wants a single child because she was: " we were at the centre of our family and we were accustomed to all of us.
We are not used to care for others and we do not really want to take care of others. "
Chen Zijian, 42, owner of a translation agency, explained in a more forceful.
For parents with two careers, middle class, reducing the birth rate, he said, is to have enough success to be selfish.
The people of between 20 and 30 years grew up watching the fight of their parents during the first days of the experiment of China with capitalism and do not want this kind of life for themselves, said.
Even a single child requires long of parents, argued.
A mother has to give at least two years of their social life.
Then there are issues of space, " have to reshape their apartment, and the strategic " must have a curriculum prepared for the best care when the child is 9 months. "
Most of his friends are ready to face this once, said Chen, but not two.
Ours is the first generation with the highest standard of living, said.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
A group of the UN outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The climate conference sponsored by the UN, marked so far by challenging positions and mutual recrimination, a renewed focus on Friday with the release of a document which provides ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations that carry on their shoulders the bulk of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders come to Copenhagen next week.
Prepared by an ad hoc working group of the UN, the text does not talk about how much money the rich to poor countries to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a range of options for the key questions, including how the developed economies and major emerging economies recortarían its production of coal, and what would be the limit of the global rise in temperature that policymakers would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility in the process, said John Coequyt, high representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the document of six pages, summed up a negotiating text of 180 pages to concentrate on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as " the big picture. "
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which the industrialized nations recortarían collectively their emissions by 2020 between 25 and 45 per cent, compared with 1990 levels, while the main developing countries reduce theirs during the same period between 15 and 30 per cent.
Together, the countries recortarían emissions by between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries to adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, on Friday was presented the same sort of verbal fireworks that have dominated the talks last week.
The US special climate envoy, Todd Stern, rejected the assertions that call for mandatory cuts in emissions of greenhouse gases by industrialised countries, compared with the volunteers from the major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed world.
The manoeuvre indicated that the Obama administration is taking a harder line with China, with regard to what the Bush administration officials only two years ago.
The United States is not going to make an agreement without the major developing countries to move forward and take action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei, said that the maximum climate negotiator lacked " common sense, " or was " very irresponsible " for having said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically to deal with global warming.
With the future economic history of the world's major powers at stake, the fault lines have eruption both within the developing world, as between the industrial world and the emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies to save the planet, with China and the United States face on their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the 24 most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take more courageous.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the major powers are arguing about who should pay the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even when the vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to contain the big emitters accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game where is developing a new economic hegemony, argued Ulate, who also works as a regional adviser on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that the talks will be at best a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, produced a preliminary draft Treaty of 24 pages early in the morning of Friday.
Artur Runge - Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the thrust of the small island nations has " political pressure on the political process, " in part because they are now consolidated and demand action from the emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the outstanding issues before the heads of government to close a deal.
The high - level officials, as the Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese vice minister, fell from the aircraft and ran into the corridors of the beautiful center, closed meetings and press conferences, in order to define the claims that during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where every day 13,000 people entering and leaving the Convention centre, the activists concerning the guitar performances night to flout the countries which they are selling, and are preliminary proposals of hand instead of mail) , poses a challenge.
The intensity only built: almost all key ministers are here at the moment, and on Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice - president for global policy of Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
The first train to 225 kmh of Great Britain redefines that feeling of Monday
To 5.13 on Monday morning, a perforará darkness to point a way out of train that marks a revolution for travel in Britain.
The first high - speed intercity train the country will reach 225 kmh, when as a bolt from Ashford, Kent, the St Panrcas station in London, covering 93 kilometres in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Secretary of transportation, is joining the lady Kelly Holmes, aboard the first intercity service Javelin outside London.
He hoped that the new service linking Britain to an international network of fast trains, reliable and connecting the large conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected remote areas would become prosperous suburbs, the times of business travel would be shortened and the change of planes and cars to rail would reduce domestic emissions of coal, as well as the congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties believe in this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable battle of planning and fears about environmental damage, can curb the high - speed lines in Britain.
High Speed Two (Hs2) , a company created in January to provide the government with a feasibility study, presented its report to Lord Adonis on 30 December, according to the times.
This will provide a detailed itinerary of the next phase planned for the high - speed network.
The new line linking London to the West Midlands will be drawn within a radius of five metres in urban areas and areas where the environmental impact can be controversial.
In rural areas, the plan will be fleshed out within a radius of 25 metres of a definitive map.
Hs2 is also expected to establish three options for a high - speed network broader approach to the North.
Lord Adonis will respond in spring.
The favoured option is being proposed is a configuration with, and in which a single high - speed line would reach the West Midlands.
The line was split in or near Birmingham, with a branch to the West from the Peninos to Manchester and Scotland, and another towards the north - east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would come to Scotland.
" It seems that this option would be more beneficial, " said a member of the railways.
Once completed, journey times between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours and 40 minutes.
The first tranche, which is not before 2025, would allow passengers travelling between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared with the little more than an hour.
The proposals would allow trains to travel to 402 kmh, making the British network in Europe more quickly.
The initial route is designed to withstand trains 400 Mt of length, capable of carrying people.
At least 18 trains could operate every hour in a line of.
This means that the London terminal capable of receiving 20,000 passengers per hour.
Given the restrictions of area of the capital, is expected to extend an existing station to conform to the high - speed network.
The railway industry experts argue that only the St Pancras International station or Euston offer that potential.
Lord Adonis announced whether he believes that the scheme should proceed, but a broad public consultation and planning procedures mean that a final decision will not be taken until after a general election.
Even if the work is implemented, the network would have to be built in sections.
The principle would make the trains to stop the rapid the existing lanes north of Birmingham, maintaining the journey times between London and Scotland over three hours.
This is seen as a crucial point needed to secure a change of planes to trains, a reference point for the revolution.
