US: a panel of sarcophagus that belonged to Zola was sold in USD 1.5 million
A panel of Roman sarcophagus that belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was sold on Thursday at $1.5 million, well above the estimated price, announced the dealer of art of Sotheby's.
This panel of 2 metres long by 63 cm high, dates from the third century after Christ, and its price was estimated between 150,000 and $250,000.
The marble " that represents four scenes dionisíacas, in a sophisticated architectural framework, surrounded by sátiros and women, is a rare piece, as in the world, there are only four or five, " explained on Tuesday to the AFP Florent Heintz, vice - president of auctions of art of ancient Rome and Egypt in Sotheby's.
Was sold between a hundred lots.
The sale continues, but until now, this batch was the most pujado by buyers, without doubt, told the AFP a Sotheby's spokesman, Dan Abernethy.
Only a few days ago, it was discovered that the marble was an acquisition of Emile Zola.
For almost 300 years, the panel formed part of the famous collection of the family Borges in Rome, then appeared in the home of the French actress, as an element of their bath in particular Paris mansion, and in the home of Paul Raynaud, Minister of the French Republic and President of the Council for a short time, before the power.
For some 50 years, their fate was uncertain.
Reviewing the database of the Louvre Museum, Florent Heintz discovered that this panel was part of a " succession Emile Zola " opened in 1903, a year after the death of the author of " Thérèse Raquin " and the fresh Rougon - macquart ".
