So far has not received a response, it was said.
The Ministry on Saturday was expressed to the criticisms to make, and suggested that this be clarified in the Federal Parliament's Committee of inquiry, which will be the next Wednesday.
Worlds Oníricos
In a state of vigilance, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts fade the boundaries between fantasy and reality.
While during the dream, everything is in order.
When we are acostados in our rooms dark with our eyes closed, we can without hindrance to the more wild imaginations and creations of the fantasy.
However, who experience States similar to the dream during the vigil, or see and hear things that others do not see or hear, is considered the most modern in the Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as maniático.
But such images and voices not only arise in the mentally ill or drugged.
The blame lies our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, sometimes are blurring the boundaries between the dream, madness and reality.
The states of consciousness alert modified can appear in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases, call visions, and at worst, madness.
Although it can distinguish the trigger and effects, it can refer to similar processes such visions of the Hildegard von Bingen, experiences psicodélicas of the prophet of the new era Carlos Castañeda, states of possession, and the psychosis and hallucinations.
The hallucinations or delusions arise when it has the balance of the neural substances of communication in the brain - above all, noradrenaline, dopamine, serotonin and acetilcolina - and is the interaction between different parts of the same.
During a schizophrenic psychosis very often appear hallucinations complex thoughts and crazed.
The gravity no longer has power over him
The relationship between madness and dream has occupied the philosophers and doctors from the former era.
Aristotle approached the hallucinations as a form of sleep in a state of vigilance, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of the modern psychiatry, in 1861 a " great resemblance of the state of madness with the oníricos ', to Sigmund Freud, the dream even was " a psychosis, with all the absurdities, alocadas formations and attractions ".
It is the autumn of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a figure of comic.
His body is two dimensions and scandalously colourful.
The gravity no longer has power over him, is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red as blood, deformed, rechinando teeth.
They are pursuing, with heavy boots and flameantes, cast against the walls, he feels the pain throughout the body.
Voices shrill and malignant resound from the walls and the radio.
Can no longer bear the voices that insult and offend.
Henning T. pulls two cables of the stereo, to form a knot of hanged, and set in a hook on the ceiling.
You climb in a whelk and the noose around the neck.
Salta.
The rope was loose.
What you will serve as a lesson! , the voices in a chorus that the eardrums, " sees the clinic and do you! "
Now, Henning T. is 40 years and has undergone six acute psychosis, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause of death was the LSD.
His diagnosis is esquizo - afectiva - paranoide psychosis, is also maniaco - depresivo, takes drugs, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with their disease, three years ago is married.
In the psychosis have experienced the most terrible anguish and despair, said.
The hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in a lifetime of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics are as the second most common disease after the depression.
In a schizophrenic psychosis acute, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the interior, and fall into a state of anxiety that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, in the relationship, or disorders.
Particularly widespread is the hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
They are also frequent the hallucinations.
The affected is no longer able to distinguish what is important and what is not, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, awareness is inundated with impressions.
As the dream, the psychosis opens the floodgates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of the reality in the psychosis is focused on the subject, says professor Thomas Fuchs, chief doctor of the general Psychiatry clinic of Heidelberg University hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the centre of events, everything has a meaning addressed to him.
At the same time entering a passive role, as in a dream, feels overwhelmed by events and not organise actively.
That is why the schizophrenic often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust the reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, the impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, he says, " the spatial and sensory structure of the reality in the psychosis remain in principle. "
The paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in reality.
For researchers still unknown why our brains for mishaps.
According to Fuchs, the states of emergency can lead to any person to lose touch with reality.
But not all people develop a psychosis.
Apparently there is a genetic provision for schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that in addition to the genes there are also other determinants.
The researchers assume that those affected suffer brain damage.
We suspect that the neural maturity of the brain is in an early stage of development, for example through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains unknown how this alteration of the neural system, which manifests itself in all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role - the stress or a traumatic experience can be the trigger psychosis when there is already a provision.
In the same way, the hallucinogenic drugs can lead to psychosis, as they interfere in the system of the brain.
When the brain warms
The illogical of all this is that the people are with their hallucinations and take medicines very expensive to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says professor in psychology Erich Kasten, Lübeck.
The perceived a hallucination as pleasant or not often hinges on the point of view.
Kasten collects from ten years ago reports of hallucinations and visions and has analysed the results in the paper die irreale Welt in unserem (the unreal world in our head) , published last year.
The hallucinations are among the typical symptoms of the psychosis, but also, surprisingly, many other diseases.
Among them are, together with mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depression, also often diseases such as tablet, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease and injuries craneoencefálicos.
In a surprising and under specific conditions, the brain healthy people also suffers hallucinations.
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, is composed of memories that normally are repressed.
Arise when the brain areas that are processed sensory perceptions are hyperactive or are little; when our brains hot, but also when stimuli.
The drugs can cause this state in the same way that the brain damage or a psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, the stress, the evil of brain or other states of emergency.
In jüngeren Studien gab bis zu einem Drittel der Befragten an mindestens
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years, lived in a small town of Mecklenburg - Western Pomerania and sent to a secondary school.
A girl.
If it were not for these images and voices.
Sometimes, during the recess, it happens that a boy clumsy with long hair and dark runs the floor.
When she replied, the other pupils look soprendidos; nobody, a part of it, hear or see the boy.
They believe that the timid girl is a ensoñadora a little strange, but Sarah K. knows that it is not dreaming.
Is awake and sees and hears that boy, in the same way that sees and hears the girl sitting in the Bank.
Can feel even their presence, at least a few moments.
It is a pleasant, like the boy.
Sometimes wonders whether it is mad.
Also knows that the boy and the rest of visions are not real and disappear.
In the evenings, appearances are alarming.
The visions are often a burden.
When class sometimes cannot follow the lesson because Professor - their eyes and ears - is presenting a new colleague, while for the rest explains so visible and audible the mathematical equations.
In the evenings, appearances are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room to reach the dream, which often comes too late and is low, not know if it is happening or dreaming, the images that we see, the nose or the girl with cuts in arms and legs, appear to their eyes open or closed.
Leave me in peace, shouts to the figures.
To Their parents and friends told you nothing, that is insane.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. has hoy20 years.
Approved last year selectivity and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago that the hallucinations have disappeared.
Since he has come in contact through the Internet with the psychologist Kasten, knows that it is not crazy.
The madness is also a work of art by despair.
According to Kasten, when a person is isolated socially or suffers a restriction of incentives, it is very likely that after a time begins to have hallucinations.
I believe that the brain is emptied yse charged the same sought entertainment.
Sarah K., daughter only, had little fear of the other children and often played alone.
Their hallucinations began when, with 13 years, learned that the man called Daddy since that use of the reason is not his biological father.
Since the noise and visual hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noise, as Sarah K. it is difficult to distinguish between vision and reality. " Every experience, " says Kasten, " takes place in the brain, the reality is projected there.
The hallucinations are equally images that the brain produces, that seem so real. "
Kasten also classifies the night fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike the schizophrenic, healthy people are able to recognise their visions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore recommends patients appreciate their hallucinations as a special skill.
Situation between dream and hallucination
In this world too focused on what is aware, the experiences often generally patologizarse, says Michael Schmidt - degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the hospital's psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic Florence - nightingale - krankenhauses in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful but that also involves something positive and creative - the madness is a masterpiece of despair.
Schmidt - degenhard has investigated the so - called oneirismo, a special form of awareness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
The Oníricas hallucinations are almost dreams very detailed and complex that the person experiences considers real and subsequently cannot differentiate from staying.
The States aware oníricos arise in extreme situations associated with a trauma or a disease, as for example in patients with polirradiculoneuropatía, experiencing a paralysis remain completely aware. die Eibâs.
According to Schmidt - degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of oneself or of the world due to a motor disability total and permanent, it replaces a real situation very dangerous by an imaginary world and that is decoupled from reality.
A form of extreme situation between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change in the world, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive to give meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation in itself that our own ability allows us not sink into nothing of the loss of awareness.
Everything is real, even later in the memory
Also the historian of art Peter Cornelius Claussen, Zurich, described their experiences oníricas in his book Herzenwechsel as of a rescue of the soul.
Had 49 years, when his conscience embarked on trips of several days after an operation of the heart valves with heart transplant included, while his body was sentenced to immobility in the intensive care.
Claussen descended into a world created by the same and visited once strange places: was caved in a bed, an older man aboard a sanatorium in a train, a robot for their health.
Was in the high Middle Ages, surrounded by noble produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorbike was kidnapped in their country of origin, surfing on his hospital bed in the Alps with snow and found with a Korean Mafia.
What gives these facts on imaginary, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these trips interioresson fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is a different state, describes his experience.
On the contrary, the memories of the trips are mental, many years later, much more clear, even in the details irrelevant.
Even More clear and intensive that actual experiences.
The intensity of this experience diluted the horizon of the rest of our everyday experience, adds the psychiatrist Schmidt - degenhard.
Finally, the oneirismo, psychosis, hallucinations and consumption of narcotic drugs show how fragile the internal reproduction of the reality outside, even when we are awake.
Every amendment of the state of consciousness, summarises the psychologist Kasten, " can lead to a distortion of what we call reality. "
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
