The promise of Fonpeek
Peek is extremely limited, a device that serves only to look at the post, without even seeing some kind of Deputy or surf the net.
Enjoyed his five minutes of fame in the US when Time magazine named one of the products of the year.
See on the street is more difficult, the truth, but the idea can be interesting, especially for young people.
Unlike the smartphones, Peek has a very low price and a very low monthly fee, less than half of what is paid, for example, the iPhone data plan.
Given the success the company has brought two new devices: one exclusively designed to Twitter, the other with a free service of data for life in exchange for paying six times more for the Peek.
Fonpeek, presented yesterday in the event, is the European version of the invention and its third encarnaciónn.
It is equally limited than its American counterpart, but it comes with a surprise.
The price of monthly maintenance, of about 12 euros a month, includes the roaming across Europe.
Those travelling with a smartphones already know what it is like to have to give up the data when it crosses the border or desperately seeking a cafeteria with WiFi (or a Fon) to consult the mail.
The idea of a roaming to fixed price is incredibly attractive and long ago that would have to be in operation.
Yes, some operators have special arrangements and travel plans, but in my experience it takes a doctorate in physics to understand and good glasses to read the small print.
The repeated of ears of the European Commission to achieve affordable roaming prices for the whole of Europe have hardly had a noticeable effect.
Outside the country of origin are afraid to use the data, and rightly so.
That a aparatito as Fonpeek (it is curious that bear the name of Fon when lacks Wifi) achieves this kind of charges means that operators are starting to think differently and studying different proposals to data network.
Kindle is another good example, includes the trafficking of unloading of books and other consultations on the Internet.
Without contracts and bagpipes.
It is a connected device and paid for it to buy it, month to month.
And that is what I hope to see one day with Fonpeek, an option to purchase with access for life as Peek already has in US
Not because there will buy it.
I watch my post in the telephone, thank you.
I hope so, because I think that it is a fairer model for the consumer.
It would be interesting to see a computer with this same system.
