75% of working mothers has had problems for their maternity
Discrimination in the workplace has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
It reveals the study ' fertility and work history of women in Spain ', developed by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of women.
The survey conducted between 9.737 women from 15 to 75 years leaves no doubt about it: 75% of working mothers has seen limited opportunities in the workplace because of motherhood.
The study notes that there are many differences in the beginning of coexistence of couples and the number of children, depending on whether or not work and the type of work.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, working part - time, or have a stable work, initiated before the coexistence, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delaying the coexistence and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
" women between 35 and 49 years with permanent work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that rises to 4.1 women with permanent jobs have needed more time record vital to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the Union and the arrival of the children.
Moreover, the type of work performed exerts great influence on motherhood although less about the timing of the pairing, " explains the researcher of the Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that unlike the age of women to marry and have the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the greater the age at marriage and have their first child.
The difference is also among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group of between 35 and 49 years, which have elementary and higher education have been mothers for the first time in the middle of 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
" It also provides another division between women depending on their level of education.
While those with elementary school, marry and have their first child before achieving a stable employment, the average levels or higher invest this sequence and give priority to ensuring a stable job as a precondition to marriage and the arrival of a child ", detailing Delgado.
